            <div type="note" subtype="bibliographical">
                <head type="title"><orgName corresp="#SOTHEBYS">Sotheby&#x02BC;s</orgName> Sale of <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> Pictures and Drawings, <date when="1931">1931</date></head>
                <p>On <date when="1931-05-20">20 May 1931</date>, <orgName corresp="#SOTHEBYS">Sotheby &#x0026; Co.</orgName> held a sale of paintings and drawings by or belonging to <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>, 
                    two days following the <ref type="note" subtype="bibliographical" target="provenance_sothebys_1931_note.php"><orgName corresp="#SOTHEBYS">Sotheby&#x02BC;s</orgName> Sale of <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> Manuscripts and Library, <date when="1930">1931</date></ref>. 
                    As described in the title of the 1931 catalogue, the sale represented 
                    <ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#SOTHEBYCAT1931PICTURES"><title type="catalogue" corresp="#SOTHEBYCAT1931"><hi rend="italic">The Collection of Pictures and Drawings, Formerly the Property of the Late <persName corresp="#JR">Professor John Ruskin</persName>, 
                        Removed from <placeName type="building" corresp="#BRANTWOOD">Brantwood</placeName>, <placeName corresp="#CONISTON">Coniston</placeName> (Sold by Order of the Trustees), and the Property of the Late <persName corresp="#AS">Joseph Arthur Palliser&#x2010;Severn</persName>, R.I., R.O.I., 
                        Removed from <placeName type="building" corresp="#9WARWICKSQ">9, Warwick Square</placeName>, <placeName corresp="#LONDON">London</placeName>, S.W.</hi></title></ref>.</p>
                
                <p>On 21 May, the day following the sale, the B. F. Stevens &#x0026; Brown firm cabled Goodspeed that they had "secured cream collection comprising about seventy framed items". 
                    The firm specified that they "bought all lots specially wanted except onefourfour [lot 144]". The especially desired items included George Richmond's two portraits of Ruskin--the 
                    1857 chalk head portrait (lot 29) for &#x00A3;33, and the 1842 full-length portrait (lot 30) for &#x00A3;82. The total was 25 purchases for a little over &#x00A3;700 
                    (<title type="letter" corresp="brown_to_goodspeed_1931-05-21">telegram, <orgName corresp="BFSTEVENSBROWN">B. F. Stevens &#x0026; Brown</orgName> to <persName corresp="#CG">Goodspeed</persName>, <date when="1931-05-21">21 May 1931</date></title>, 
                    in <ref type="bibiography" target="bibliography.php#BROWNALSTOGOODSPEEDBEINECKE">Stevens, B. F., and Brown. Letters, telegrams, and other materials to Charles Goodspeed</ref>; and see 
                    <ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#SOTHEBYCAT1931PICTURES"><orgName corresp="#SOTHEBYS">Sotheby &#x0026; Co.</orgName>, <title type="catalogue" corresp="#SOTHEBYCAT1931"><hi rend="italic">Catalogue of the Collection of Pictures and Drawings . . . of the Late <persName corresp="#JR">Professor John Ruskin</persName></hi></title></ref>). 
                </p>
                
                
